05177nam a22008175i 9780231540346DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315403467 a10.7312/dang175822doi  a(DE-B1597)499054  a(OCoLC)1023541760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBH301.S66bD3613 2018eb 7aART0090002bisacsh04a111/.852231 aD'Angelo, Paolo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSprezzatura :bConcealing the Effort of Art from Aristotle to Duchamp /cPaolo D'Angelo. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface to the First Edition -- tNote to the Second Italian Edition -- t1 Concealment -- t2 Part of Eloquence Is to Hide Eloquence -- t3 The Concealed Ornament -- t4 Art or Nature? -- t5 In the Garden -- t6 Iki -- t7 Those Who Cannot Dissimulate Cannot Rule Either -- t8 True Eloquence Mocks Eloquence -- t9 Ready-Mades -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essence of art is to conceal art. A dancer or musician does not only need to perform with ability. There should also be a lack of visible effort that gives an impression of naturalness. To disguise technique and feign ease is to heighten beauty. To express this notion, Italian has a word with no exact equivalent in other languages, sprezzatura: a kind of unaffectedness or nonchalance.In this book, the first to consider sprezzatura in its own right, philosopher of art Paolo D’Angelo reconstructs the history of concealing art, from ancient rhetoric to our own times. The word sprezzatura was coined in 1528 by Baldassarre Castiglione in The Book of the Courtier to mean a kind of grace with a special essence: the ability to conceal art. But the idea reaches back to Aristotle and Cicero and forward to avant-garde works such as Duchamp’s ready-mades, all of which share the suspicion of the overt display of skill. The precept that art must be hidden turns up in a number of fields, from cosmetics to interior design, politics to poetry, the English garden to shabby chic. Through exploring different articulations of this idea, D’Angelo shows the paradox of aesthetics: art hides that it is art, but in doing so it reveals itself to be art and becomes an assertion about art. When art is concealed, it appears as spontaneous as nature—yet, paradoxically, also reveals its indebtedness to technique. An erudite and surprising tour through aesthetics, philosophy, and art history, Sprezzatura presents a strikingly original argument with deceptive ease.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aSprezzatura (Aesthetics). 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2018z9783110602999oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishz978311060397208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/dang1758240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231540346423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231540346.jpg  a978-3-11-060397-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia